1
00:01:10,649 --> 00:01:11,946
On the other side
of the world...

2
00:01:11,984 --> 00:01:15,613
in Europe the Allied forces
are pounding the Germans...

3
00:01:15,654 --> 00:01:17,451
with relentless force.

4
00:01:17,489 --> 00:01:21,289
We do not expect to have
a winter lull in Europe.

5
00:01:21,326 --> 00:01:23,624
We expect to
keep striking...

6
00:01:23,662 --> 00:01:25,289
to keep the enemy
on the move...

7
00:01:25,330 --> 00:01:26,797
and hit him again
and again.

8
00:01:26,832 --> 00:01:29,130
1944, December.

9
00:01:29,168 --> 00:01:30,294
I was miles
from the front...

10
00:01:30,335 --> 00:01:31,962
and a stranger to war.

11
00:01:32,004 --> 00:01:33,631
Troops, fuel dumps...

12
00:01:33,672 --> 00:01:34,798
enemy units...

13
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:36,808
they were pins
on a map to me.

14
00:01:36,842 --> 00:01:38,002
Champagne?

15
00:01:39,011 --> 00:01:40,478
Are you trying
to score a few points?

16
00:01:40,512 --> 00:01:42,639
Just trying to aid
the war effort, Hart.

17
00:01:42,681 --> 00:01:43,807
Tom.

18
00:01:43,849 --> 00:01:44,975
Sir.

19
00:01:45,017 --> 00:01:46,314
The captain needs a lift
back to the 106th.

20
00:01:46,351 --> 00:01:47,818
Can you find him a driver?

21
00:01:47,853 --> 00:01:49,650
I can take him, sir.

22
00:01:49,688 --> 00:01:51,315
Funny. I had a feeling
you'd say that.

23
00:01:51,356 --> 00:01:53,324
Well, there hasn't been
much movement today, sir.

24
00:01:53,358 --> 00:01:55,155
So I see. Captain.

25
00:01:55,194 --> 00:01:56,320
Oh, don't forget, sir.

26
00:01:56,361 --> 00:01:57,885
You wanted to send some of that
champagne along as well.

27
00:02:00,032 --> 00:02:01,158
Yes.

28
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:03,134
Yes, thank you
for reminding me, Tom.

29
00:02:04,303 --> 00:02:05,793
The general should get
a kick out of that.

30
00:02:07,139 --> 00:02:08,265
Colonel.

31
00:02:08,307 --> 00:02:09,433
Troops are now fighting...

32
00:02:09,475 --> 00:02:13,104
along a battle line
of 300 miles in Poland...

33
00:02:13,145 --> 00:02:15,113
France, and Germany.

34
00:02:15,147 --> 00:02:17,615
Within 10 weeks
after the first landings

35
00:02:17,649 --> 00:02:19,947
in France last June,

36
00:02:19,985 --> 00:02:24,115
the Allies have landed
nearly 2 million men.

37
00:02:31,663 --> 00:02:33,290
You know what
this army could use, sir?

38
00:02:33,332 --> 00:02:34,629
Snowplow services.

39
00:02:34,666 --> 00:02:35,792
What we could use...

40
00:02:35,834 --> 00:02:37,131
is half a million gallons
of gasoline...

41
00:02:37,169 --> 00:02:38,466
and a road
that wasn't paved...

42
00:02:38,504 --> 00:02:39,664
for Bouncing Betties.

43
00:02:41,840 --> 00:02:43,307
German S-mines.

44
00:02:43,342 --> 00:02:44,502
Yes, sir.

45
00:02:45,344 --> 00:02:46,641
You really ought
to spend a night...

46
00:02:46,678 --> 00:02:47,838
on the line sometime,
Lieutenant.

47
00:02:49,348 --> 00:02:50,815
I know that, sir.

48
00:02:50,849 --> 00:02:53,477
Of course,
it's not too likely, is it?

49
00:02:53,519 --> 00:02:54,679
Sir?

50
00:02:55,687 --> 00:02:57,814
The Colonel says
your father is a senator.

51
00:02:57,856 --> 00:02:59,323
So I guess you won't
spend too many nights...

52
00:02:59,358 --> 00:03:00,848
in a foxhole, will you?

53
00:03:03,295 --> 00:03:05,263
It's nothing
to be ashamed of, son.

54
00:03:05,297 --> 00:03:07,128
That's a hell
of a father to have.

55
00:03:30,989 --> 00:03:32,650
- Where to, sir?
- St. Vith.

56
00:03:33,825 --> 00:03:35,793
I'm afraid you've gone
the wrong way, sir.

57
00:03:35,827 --> 00:03:37,158
St. Vith is due west.

58
00:03:39,498 --> 00:03:42,160
I'm pretty sure
St. Vith is due east.

59
00:03:43,335 --> 00:03:45,166
Sergeant,
it's straight ahead.

60
00:03:46,004 --> 00:03:47,164
Can I see that, sir?

61
00:03:53,845 --> 00:03:56,473
I drove this route
yesterday, Sergeant.

62
00:03:56,515 --> 00:03:57,675
Mm-hmm.

63
00:04:07,459 --> 00:04:08,619
Get your hands up.

64
00:04:10,128 --> 00:04:11,288
Out!

65
00:04:32,317 --> 00:04:33,477
Halt!

66
00:06:15,513 --> 00:06:16,844
Are you in great pain?

67
00:06:18,349 --> 00:06:19,976
First Lieutenant...

68
00:06:20,018 --> 00:06:21,815
Thomas Hart.

69
00:06:21,853 --> 00:06:23,013
Serial number...

70
00:06:24,355 --> 00:06:27,847
1841287.

71
00:06:31,029 --> 00:06:32,360
Would you care
for a cigarette?

72
00:06:34,866 --> 00:06:37,357
Your train is
an 8 kilometer march from here.

73
00:06:38,369 --> 00:06:40,166
Of course,
with some shoes on...

74
00:06:40,204 --> 00:06:41,364
you might be all right.

75
00:06:43,374 --> 00:06:45,171
First Lieutenant...

76
00:06:45,209 --> 00:06:46,369
Thomas Hart.

77
00:06:47,712 --> 00:06:51,705
Serial number 1841287.

78
00:06:52,717 --> 00:06:54,344
Thank you, Lieutenant.

79
00:06:54,385 --> 00:06:56,012
But we both know...

80
00:06:56,054 --> 00:06:57,885
there is much more
to you than that.

81
00:07:04,329 --> 00:07:06,661
Show me locations
of the fuel dumps.

82
00:07:08,666 --> 00:07:10,293
Just point...

83
00:07:10,335 --> 00:07:11,666
and we can end all this.

84
00:07:35,760 --> 00:07:37,523
I'll have your clothes
returned to you immediately.

85
00:07:38,529 --> 00:07:40,190
When you are dressed,
we'll have another chat.

86
00:07:41,032 --> 00:07:42,192
Our last one, I hope.

87
00:08:03,988 --> 00:08:05,285
Smile, Joe.

88
00:08:05,323 --> 00:08:06,756
For you the war is over.

89
00:08:49,033 --> 00:08:50,022
Lieutenant.

90
00:08:50,868 --> 00:08:52,199
This will help
against the cold.

91
00:08:53,704 --> 00:08:55,331
No thanks, soldier.

92
00:08:55,373 --> 00:08:56,499
I'll be all right.

93
00:08:56,541 --> 00:08:57,667
No, you won't.

94
00:08:57,708 --> 00:08:58,834
Come on. Take it.

95
00:08:58,876 --> 00:09:00,343
Just till you warm up.

96
00:09:00,378 --> 00:09:01,504
Take it, sir.

97
00:09:20,665 --> 00:09:21,791
Hey, Captain...

98
00:09:21,833 --> 00:09:24,631
does somebody tell our folks
about us being captured?

99
00:09:24,669 --> 00:09:26,296
Germans give a list
to the military...

100
00:09:26,337 --> 00:09:28,464
and the military
notifies the family.

101
00:09:28,506 --> 00:09:29,837
Is that voluntary, sir?

102
00:09:31,175 --> 00:09:32,472
How do you mean,
Lieutenant?

103
00:09:32,510 --> 00:09:34,307
Uh, I mean...

104
00:09:34,345 --> 00:09:35,676
can you ask them not to?

105
00:09:38,182 --> 00:09:39,342
I don't think so.

106
00:10:06,711 --> 00:10:08,542
Have to put
some straw in there.

107
00:10:10,047 --> 00:10:12,845
Straw in your shoes...

108
00:10:12,884 --> 00:10:14,044
for frostbite.

109
00:10:44,648 --> 00:10:45,945
Another slave detail, sir.

110
00:10:48,485 --> 00:10:49,782
Hey, ladies...

111
00:10:49,820 --> 00:10:51,287
next batch of shells
you turn out...

112
00:10:51,322 --> 00:10:53,449
nothing but duds
this time, all right?

113
00:10:53,490 --> 00:10:55,321
Mortars no boom boom, ja?

114
00:11:00,164 --> 00:11:01,290
Fire!

115
00:11:01,332 --> 00:11:03,391
Captain, P-51 incoming.

116
00:11:03,434 --> 00:11:04,731
- Incoming!
- Ours?

117
00:11:04,768 --> 00:11:05,894
Get down, everybody!

118
00:11:05,936 --> 00:11:07,096
Get down!

119
00:11:16,447 --> 00:11:18,176
Everybody stay down!

120
00:11:18,215 --> 00:11:19,375
Keep low!

121
00:11:24,288 --> 00:11:25,585
Captain, what's happening?

122
00:11:25,623 --> 00:11:26,749
Why are they
shooting at us?

123
00:11:26,790 --> 00:11:27,950
They can't read the roof.

124
00:11:32,463 --> 00:11:34,090
All right, get the doors!

125
00:11:34,131 --> 00:11:36,429
Everybody get the doors!

126
00:11:36,467 --> 00:11:37,627
Come on, now!

127
00:11:38,469 --> 00:11:39,629
Get down!

128
00:11:44,541 --> 00:11:45,838
Get down! Down!

129
00:11:49,813 --> 00:11:50,973
Hart, help out!

130
00:11:59,056 --> 00:12:00,683
- Come on!
- Go! Go! Go!

131
00:12:17,441 --> 00:12:19,102
Go on, now!
Let's go!

132
00:12:21,278 --> 00:12:22,404
Moving out!

133
00:12:22,446 --> 00:12:24,209
Get the other cars!

134
00:12:29,286 --> 00:12:30,753
Get the other cars!

135
00:12:30,788 --> 00:12:32,085
Let's go! Now!

136
00:12:32,122 --> 00:12:33,851
We're spelling out!

137
00:12:33,891 --> 00:12:36,086
Round up your men now!

138
00:12:36,126 --> 00:12:38,094
We're spelling out
our position!

139
00:12:38,128 --> 00:12:39,288
We're spelling out!

140
00:12:40,130 --> 00:12:42,758
Hart, get that man
clear of here.

141
00:12:42,800 --> 00:12:44,427
Let's get in line!

142
00:12:44,468 --> 00:12:45,935
Assemble on me!

143
00:12:45,969 --> 00:12:48,028
- Assemble!
- Move it! Move it!

144
00:12:58,315 --> 00:12:59,612
All right, men!

145
00:12:59,650 --> 00:13:01,174
Let's get back in line!

146
00:13:01,752 --> 00:13:02,741
Move it!

147
00:13:27,311 --> 00:13:29,711
It's not helping.

148
00:13:30,781 --> 00:13:31,941
Come on, men!

149
00:13:59,710 --> 00:14:01,011
Oh, Christ.

150
00:14:01,144 --> 00:14:02,111
Are you OK?

151
00:14:02,145 --> 00:14:03,772
Keep looking at me.
Look at me.

152
00:14:03,813 --> 00:14:04,973
Look at me.

153
00:14:06,249 --> 00:14:07,910
Oh, shit. Shit.

154
00:14:07,951 --> 00:14:10,317
All right.
Are you all right?

155
00:14:33,843 --> 00:14:35,174
They're telling us to march.

156
00:14:36,179 --> 00:14:38,044
Probably ought to take
his boots, Lieutenant.

157
00:14:40,350 --> 00:14:41,647
Lieutenant!

158
00:14:41,685 --> 00:14:43,653
Take his boots.

159
00:14:43,687 --> 00:14:45,484
'Cause either you
or some Jerry's gonna get 'em.

160
00:14:45,522 --> 00:14:46,648
Take 'em, sir...

161
00:14:46,690 --> 00:14:48,351
while you still got feet
to put 'em on.

162
00:14:49,693 --> 00:14:50,819
His socks, too.

163
00:14:50,860 --> 00:14:52,191
Ain't gonna help him any.

164
00:14:53,029 --> 00:14:54,189
Stay together.

165
00:14:56,700 --> 00:14:57,860
All right.

166
00:17:09,632 --> 00:17:10,792
Once again...

167
00:17:12,302 --> 00:17:17,467
I'm forced to remind you
escape is not a sport.

168
00:17:28,318 --> 00:17:29,478
Think of it this way.

169
00:17:30,653 --> 00:17:32,621
Now these Russians
have a chance...

170
00:17:32,655 --> 00:17:34,145
at a happy new year.

171
00:17:50,340 --> 00:17:52,331
Those are dogs
you're saluting, Colonel.

172
00:17:53,843 --> 00:17:55,003
Animals.

173
00:17:58,848 --> 00:17:59,974
My country doesn't make...

174
00:18:00,016 --> 00:18:01,483
those kinds of
distinctions, Colonel.

175
00:18:14,464 --> 00:18:15,795
They're our allies, Colonel.

176
00:18:16,800 --> 00:18:19,291
Oh, yes.
You and your allies.

177
00:18:20,637 --> 00:18:23,470
Let me tell you
about you and your allies.

178
00:18:27,310 --> 00:18:30,939
The Ministry of War
has just released the figures...

179
00:18:30,980 --> 00:18:32,641
from our offensive
in the Ardennes.

180
00:18:33,817 --> 00:18:37,116
Two hundred thousand Allies
killed or captured.

181
00:18:37,153 --> 00:18:38,279
Your Third Army...

182
00:18:38,321 --> 00:18:40,448
Patton...
in full retreat.

183
00:18:40,490 --> 00:18:43,948
And the wehrmacht has captured
enough abundant fuel...

184
00:18:43,993 --> 00:18:45,290
to retake Paris...

185
00:18:45,328 --> 00:18:47,819
perhaps even drive
your troops back to the sea.

186
00:18:49,165 --> 00:18:51,998
Might be a bit crowded
around here this winter.

187
00:19:08,117 --> 00:19:09,243
Turn around, Joes.

188
00:19:09,285 --> 00:19:11,378
Yes. Turn around.

189
00:19:19,629 --> 00:19:21,119
Ross. Hart.

190
00:19:22,966 --> 00:19:24,763
Ross and Hart.

191
00:19:24,801 --> 00:19:25,961
I'm Captain Ross.

192
00:19:27,303 --> 00:19:28,600
Major Clary.

193
00:19:28,638 --> 00:19:29,764
Lieutenant Hart.

194
00:19:29,806 --> 00:19:31,603
Lieutenant.

195
00:19:31,641 --> 00:19:33,108
Debriefing, gentleman.
Officer's hut.

196
00:19:33,142 --> 00:19:34,871
On the double.

197
00:19:34,911 --> 00:19:36,846
The German counterattack on
the American Third Army front...

198
00:19:36,846 --> 00:19:37,437
The German counterattack on
the American Third Army front...

199
00:19:37,480 --> 00:19:38,606
is still going on.

200
00:19:38,648 --> 00:19:39,774
The entire front...

201
00:19:39,816 --> 00:19:41,943
stretching about
30 miles south of Monschau...

202
00:19:41,985 --> 00:19:43,111
is in full view.

203
00:19:43,152 --> 00:19:45,450
On our side,
countermeasures are being taken.

204
00:19:45,488 --> 00:19:48,787
On the enemy's side,
more strafes are being flown in.

205
00:19:48,825 --> 00:19:51,123
This is a major German effort.

206
00:19:51,160 --> 00:19:52,787
Some of the best units
in the German army...

207
00:19:52,829 --> 00:19:54,319
were involved
in this penetration.

208
00:19:55,832 --> 00:19:56,958
At ease, soldier.

209
00:19:57,000 --> 00:19:58,160
Sit down.

210
00:20:02,338 --> 00:20:03,498
Thank you, sir.

211
00:20:07,343 --> 00:20:08,674
So tell me, Lieutenant...

212
00:20:10,513 --> 00:20:11,673
How come you're not dead?

213
00:20:12,515 --> 00:20:13,675
Sir?

214
00:20:15,184 --> 00:20:16,811
First you survive
crashing that jeep...

215
00:20:16,853 --> 00:20:18,980
then Hans and Fritz
take your boots.

216
00:20:19,022 --> 00:20:20,853
You got a rabbit's foot
in your pocket, son?

217
00:20:22,692 --> 00:20:24,990
Two horseshoes
and a 4-leaf clover, sir.

218
00:20:25,028 --> 00:20:26,188
Atta boy.

219
00:20:27,196 --> 00:20:28,322
By the way...

220
00:20:28,364 --> 00:20:29,695
you might want to take it easy
on that bread.

221
00:20:30,700 --> 00:20:33,168
You haven't had anything
solid for a while.

222
00:20:33,202 --> 00:20:35,329
Wouldn't want you to wind up
in the infirmary.

223
00:20:35,371 --> 00:20:36,531
I don't know, sir.

224
00:20:37,707 --> 00:20:39,675
After the march I just made...

225
00:20:39,709 --> 00:20:42,041
and infirmary might look
like the Waldorf to me.

226
00:20:45,548 --> 00:20:47,709
A stomach can shrink
quite a bit in 17 days.

227
00:20:49,052 --> 00:20:50,679
That's the number, isn't it?

228
00:20:50,720 --> 00:20:52,187
Seventeen days?

229
00:20:52,221 --> 00:20:54,018
Six days on the train...

230
00:20:54,057 --> 00:20:55,854
another 6 days of marching.

231
00:20:55,892 --> 00:20:57,359
What was it, Joe?

232
00:20:57,393 --> 00:20:58,553
Five days of interrogation?

233
00:20:59,395 --> 00:21:00,555
No, sir.

234
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:05,160
Three days.

235
00:21:08,171 --> 00:21:11,163
Well, anyway...
easy does it.

236
00:21:12,508 --> 00:21:14,169
Yes, sir. Thank you.

237
00:21:15,345 --> 00:21:17,472
So this interrogator
they threw at you...

238
00:21:17,513 --> 00:21:18,844
his name wasn't Schumann,
was it?

239
00:21:24,687 --> 00:21:25,847
No, sir.

240
00:21:27,190 --> 00:21:28,350
Lutz.

241
00:21:32,028 --> 00:21:33,689
Schumann was a real prick.

242
00:21:34,530 --> 00:21:35,861
Almost broke me in two.

243
00:22:00,349 --> 00:22:02,180
Not much for small talk,
I guess.

244
00:22:02,218 --> 00:22:04,118
You come to appreciate that.

245
00:22:08,891 --> 00:22:10,051
Smoke, Lieutenant?

246
00:22:11,894 --> 00:22:13,225
Would you care
for a cigarette?

247
00:22:14,730 --> 00:22:17,221
Again, Lieutenant,
I need to ask you...

248
00:22:18,067 --> 00:22:19,227
the fuel dumps...

249
00:22:22,571 --> 00:22:23,731
Thank you.

250
00:22:26,909 --> 00:22:28,706
This Captain Lutz...

251
00:22:28,744 --> 00:22:30,905
he know much about
your operations at the chateau?

252
00:22:33,749 --> 00:22:34,909
He knew everything, sir.

253
00:22:36,252 --> 00:22:37,879
Fuel dump locations?

254
00:22:37,920 --> 00:22:39,080
Troop movements?

255
00:22:41,924 --> 00:22:43,551
Sir, he knew what
I'd had for breakfast...

256
00:22:43,592 --> 00:22:44,889
the morning of my capture.

257
00:22:52,101 --> 00:22:54,763
Point,
and we can end all this.

258
00:23:00,276 --> 00:23:02,710
Just name, rank,
and serial number.

259
00:23:07,216 --> 00:23:08,376
Good enough.

260
00:23:09,885 --> 00:23:11,045
You're excused, Lieutenant.

261
00:23:12,388 --> 00:23:13,685
Unfortunately,
we won't be able...

262
00:23:13,722 --> 00:23:14,848
to quarter you here.

263
00:23:14,890 --> 00:23:16,016
We're full up.

264
00:23:16,058 --> 00:23:17,616
We're gonna have to
put you in Barracks 27.

265
00:23:19,895 --> 00:23:22,363
Isn't barracks 27
for enlisted men, sir?

266
00:23:22,398 --> 00:23:23,524
Yes, it is...

267
00:23:23,565 --> 00:23:24,691
but as you can see...

268
00:23:24,733 --> 00:23:26,894
the Germans are doing a rather
brisk business these days.

269
00:23:27,903 --> 00:23:29,063
You'll be comfortable there.

270
00:23:30,239 --> 00:23:31,399
Sir.

271
00:23:35,744 --> 00:23:37,575
- Lieutenant.
- Sir.

272
00:24:15,718 --> 00:24:16,878
Point.

273
00:24:22,391 --> 00:24:24,188
Point or say
hello to stumps...

274
00:24:24,226 --> 00:24:25,386
for the rest
of your life.

